Patient was admitted in Jan 2017 for LE b/l cellulitis IV cephalosporin narrowed to 7 day course of oral cephalo (error in note stating left on Keflex but left of cephlosporin). Presented to Er 2-10-17 for fall and pain. Found to have right wrist fracture (dominate hand) and T3-4 rib fractures. saw by Ortho in ER and recommended brace and PT, patient declined STR. On 2-15-17 discharged to STR which was cancelled due to nausea and coffee ground emesis. Hemoglobin was monitored and GI was consulted. Patient declined an EGD. Row[2] = very pleasant 72-year-old Caucasian female with multiple medical problems including chronic coronary artery disease and antiplatelet therapy was again admitted with severe anemia.  She presented to her family physician with complaints of increasing weakness and shortness of breath and was found to have dramatically reduced hemoglobin of 6.4.  She was transferred to the emergency room for admission.  She has a background of chronic anemia and has had a very thorough gastrointestinal workup in the last several months as outlined on the history and physical and also on the consultation note from Gastroenterology Service.  We transfused her to hemoglobin over 10 and a decision was made to pursue no further invasive investigations, the likelihood of finding a culprit malformation being low.  She understands she has to have her blood count checked regularly with her family physician and that if there is a sudden or acute drop or signs of acute hemorrhage, that she should present to the emergency room early for bleeding scan.  We left her medication profile unchanged.  The remainder of the laboratory data has been dictated.  The discharge hemoglobin was 10.4 with hematocrit 32.4.
